< text>
Ya know I'm not sure if it was an off day or just my unlucky day. I ordered the Joe Pesci and the sandwich came with a nice roll, meat, a small piece of cheddar cheese and some garlic aioli. Did I miss something on the board? No lettuce tomato pickle even? I would've been fine with an entire onion wheel on the sandwich to give me a different flavor other than garlic and meat. Quite depressing to receive the sandwich as it was.

$12 for meat and bread. If it wasn't for the kind customer service at the counter, I would've put this as a one and done single star review. Just entirely disappointed in a place with a high rating and not many sandwich shops around them for competition.< /text>

< Text>
Im so happy I found a place with great sandwiches in San Francisco! This place deserves 5 stars! I got Salchipapas and it was sooo good! The sausage they use is really good, it costs around $8.75 but the portion is big! We also got the Al Capone sandwich in dutch crunch bread and it was such a good choice!!! The sandwich is packed with meats and full of flavor! We also asked to sample their chicken, expecting to get 2 small pieces of chicken but they gave us 2 full chicken legs!! WHAT? and it was so good! We are definitely coming back for the chicken and sandwich!
Service is 10/10!
Totally recommend this place!</Text>

< review>
The sandwiches are pretty quality here and the staff is incredibly friendly. The prices are comparable to other shops. Definitely beats subway into next week. Had the California and the meathead. California was good but lacked a little punch. Meat head had a lot more flavour but the cheese let it down. All in all quality food for good prices.</review>

<user>107880361735392226377</user>< Text>
Went for an estimate on replacing a car convertible top. They acted nice(that's why at least 2 stars are here)but what they estimated was ridiculously too high. I thought I would do business here being that they're local and I prefer to help out local businesses. Glad I went somewhere else that's highly reputable and over 50 years in business and its still within this county. They were very honest and quoted more than a grand less than Lotts. Other businesses I called quoted me much less than Lotts and they exclusively do upholstery and convertible tops. Again, I cant be naive thinking local businesses will be the most reasonable or fair. But at least I'm thankful they reminded me that just because you expect doing business locally you wont always get a fair deal.< /Text>

<name>Alex Rovnyansky< /name>< time>
1335658211962</time>
<Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
Lotts is incredible. I bought a new stereo at Best Buy and had it installed in my 2000 Mustang (with a Mach 460 8-speaker sound system already installed). The Best Buy tech had no idea what was going on. He initially said it would be no problem, but by the time it was installed, there was an extremely loud pop (max speaker volume) every time the stereo would turn on, when I turn on the car. Also, the volume control was extremely poor. It's supposed to go up from 1-50, but it was at max volume at volume level 6, so I only had those 6 levels to work with, and the difference between 1 and 0 was huge. The Best Buy tech said he could not fix it for all the money in the world, and that's just how the sound system works. I went to Lotts, and they said Best Buy neglected to add a voltage converter, which eliminated the popping sound, and a harness appropriate for my car, which eliminated the volume control issue. After Lotts was done, my stereo worked perfectly, like a dream. I am so 100% satisfied with their work. I recommend them to all of my friends. They were extremely professional and courteous and made pleasant conversation with me while they were working on my car.</Review>

1531274618111</time>
< Rating>
1<//Rating>
<Text>TL;DR: Scummy, don‚Äôt care how your car sounds

This review is within Google‚Äôs character limit. A slightly more detailed version of this review can be found under my Yelp account (Benjamin H).

My mom bought a 2018 Kia Soul Plus and she decided to upgrade the sound so I went to Lott's with her.

We showed our system to Dave and complained about the tinny sound. To get great sound, according to him, replacing the head-unit (HU) would be unnecessary and costly because our HU is merged with many other vehicle functions like AC. Immediately he recommended just getting new speakers. After previewing all the higher quality pairs multiple times we settled on a specific pair of speakers. For what it's worth, I thought Dave came off as arrogant and aggressive and made this process needlessly stressful and frustrating.

We left to do research for a couple days and came back. On this second day at Lott's, Tim was our helper. We decided to buy the speakers we settled on and my mom decided to buy a sub. At the last second, Tim asked if we wanted an amp too. We A/B'ed a song with and without the amp for a minute. The difference felt subtle and I bet my mom couldn't tell the difference so I said, "No thanks." In the end it was approx: $500 front speakers, $500 sub, $500 installation and other things. $1500 total.

After the installation, we quickly realized the system sounded harsher than before. The fronts and sub sounded nothing like they did in the store. We came back and complained. Only after trying to convince Tim over and over again that we know what a passable sound system sounds like, he FINALLY admitted something to us: every stock HU has its own hidden frequency/EQ bias that's meant specifically for the stock speakers so that they sound good. He said since we got new speakers without getting a new HU, these speakers were not receiving a flat signal. He said in this case, the mismatch was drastic. He also said if we had bought an amp, they could have attached a digital signal processor to it, which provides an anti-EQ curve to any stock HU's EQ curve, thus fixing the problem.

I told him it is incredibly disappointing that we are learning about this crucial information after we had already spent $1500. Without apologizing, he reminded us that he had recommended the amp and that I turned it down. I told him that the A/B he had me do was flawed because I was only listening to the amp. It had NOTHING to do with comparing a flat signal to a biased signal because both signals were flat. I said the whole process of me choosing speakers was almost pointless because it was going to sound so different attached to my HU. I emphasized that they didn‚Äôt fix the ONLY complaint we had with the stock system, which was the TINNY SOUND. Without apologizing, Tim said stock HU biases usually don't make much of a difference.

This is not only a BS excuse, but also a BS statement. See, I then realized this wasn't the first time we encountered this type of problem before at this exact same establishment. I go more into detail about this in my Yelp review, but essentially years ago, my mom had brought her previous car, a Cabrio, into Lott‚Äôs, only requesting to be able to plug in her phone to the stereo. Their installation ruined the Cabrio‚Äôs sound quality for more less the same reason the Kia currently sounded bad.

I mentioned this to Tim and he expressed no sympathy, but confirmed I was right about the Cabrio.

Tim offered to attach resistors to the tweeter wire to make the tweeters quieter, which seemed like the fixing-stereo-harshness equivalent of killing a spider on a window by shooting it with a gun, but I let him do it. He told us to keep listening and if we weren't happy with this solution, we could come back in to discuss amps and prices. (BUY BUY BUY) Instead of going back, we went to California Car Sounds in Campbell. My review of them is Chapter 2 in my never-ending saga to get my mom's car to sound professional. Spoiler alert: They're also trash.< /Text>< pictures>

<Text>Incredible selection of smoked and fresh sausages at fabulous prices. Taylor's is my only known supplier of cajun boudin sausages (blanc and spicy). These meaty rice bombs are delicious and addictive. I also get my perfectly spiced and smoked andouille sausage here.

The pork cuts like baby back and spare ribs as well as pork shoulder are fantastically fresh and beautifully trimmed. You cannot beat the price for better looking pork shoulder.

The service is great and knowledgable. The location in the Swan's Market makes a visit delightful if you want to grab a bite or drink somewhere nearby. I wished I lived closer so I could enjoy their products more regularly.< /Text><pictures>None<//pictures><resp>None</resp>< gmapID>

< review>
So this was my first ever time storing things away, the staff here at Devon are absolutely amazing. I went to a previous storage company and they didn't seem like they really had the time nor patience to actually show me what I was going to be renting. I would prefer not to knock another company on anothers page, so I will leave names out. However on a positive note, Heather and Shannon were very kind and courteous when I entered. Mind you it was like 20 minutes prior to closing, and regardless Heather was like "no problem! I'll take you out there" so with that, it basically sold me just on the fact that she was very kind and respectful even though its prior to the end of her shift. So thank you Heather G! Great job, the storage facility is very clean and the units were very clean inside with no odors or anything! I would recommend that if you're in the market for a storage, that you give them a shot, you won't be let down. The prices are reasonable and the ladies are wonderful. Keep up the great work and thank you for helping me get the right unit.< /review>

< Review>
Best food ever. It's location is the original hat. Prices are great for the food. I believe there are 9 locations & out of all the locations. I've been to 7 out of 9.

The ones I've been to we're the best. I've tried almost all of the choices. And have not been disappointed yet.

Be certain when ordering fries and onion rings. Order a small one.
Because a small one is for two and a large is for at least 4 to 5 people.

It's certain that you'll have to go back more than once to try out all the food. Because you're not going to be able to try them all out in one day.
Enjoy.<//Review>

<Review>Pastrami-centric joint serving up some great pastrami fries. They're currently operating during coronavirus both through drive through and for takeout. I would suggest calling ahead to place your order as the drive through line was long. They had our food ready in ~15 min. There was a minor issue when we called in the order; the first time, the person on the other side didn't hear us and the second time the call didn't go through. Third times a charm though, so luckily we were able to indulge.

This isn't on the menu, but if you want to have a lunch that serves 3-4 people, you can order the wet fries (the gravy it comes with is so creamy and heavy) with pastrami and cheese on top (extra for both items). The pastrami is thinly sliced and they do not skimp. They did a good job of mixing the things so that even the fries on the bottom had a mix of gravy and pastrami in there. The fries are standard cut and we're piping hot. We went into a minor food coma afterwards

It's super clean inside. They do take credit cards. Service is quick and efficient. Overall it's a good spot to partake in pastrami and treat yourself should you ever find yourself around the Brea Mall.< /Review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOznGpHaOqY--HHtpEmwfUT-1lG5TAbeos2emuh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNap86cpLysRoNerm057g6kbsG0C3KFChQLEzGW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><Response>None</Response><gmapID>0x80c2c5378d99052d:0xd9cb1762718872c0< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>

<name>C Wong<//name>< review>
This is based on safety.  I watch what businesses are doing to keep everyone safe.
Not happy that they are careless. Seems like everyone was being safe but where they fail is the interaction with public and payment. The order taker is also the cashier. So far so good as long as he does not touch anything else. Once Payment transaction is done, no wash of hands nor change of gloves. He write the ticket  then slides it down. It is contaminated.  Then at one point, the handles pull the ticket and cross contaminate everything. Same cashier tries to help by refilling drinks. They use a different cup and pour it to the customer's cup. Is that still safe considering virus is airborne?  Also cashier never changed his gloves when doing this. I am aware many places are careless and I will not go back at this time. Can not take a chance on place that do not realize what they are doing. Cashiers should either have a no touch policy or do no do anything else.<//review>

<Text>Great consistent quality and service. I've never gotten a wrong order here nor have they ever forgotten anything.
Their chili is great. I love getting chili cheese fries with pastrami on top. Their steak sandwiches are good, meat is tender, and come with a pickle (excellent pickle!). The burgers are great and larger than average.

<Response>None</Response><gmapID>0x80c2c5378d99052d:0xd9cb1762718872c0</gmapID>< Text>
I can't remember a time when The Hat wasn't a local favorite.

The food is excellent. All of it. Personally, the best is their chili-cheese fries.

I'm not exaggerating when I say I gained at LEAST 15 lbs in my mid 20's eating WAAAAAY too much chili-cheese fries with pastrami.

The Hat's Pastrami are the standard for all other Pastrami places.

Parking's just okay. Traffic in the area is terrible. But the food is worth it. It's been around for almost 70 years for a reason.<//Text>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures><resp>None<//resp>< gmapID>

</record>

< GmapID>
0x80c2c5378d99052d:0xd9cb1762718872c0< /GmapID>
<pics>None<//pics>< Review>
SERVICE:  I was the only customer and the person who took my order (an older man who appeared to be the manager) was not friendly at all.  However, the food was served fast and the young man who handed me my food was friendly.
PRICES:  I ordered a regular pastrami sandwich (their specialty), small fries and a medium drink.  I paid $18.36 - WOW.  I found this to be overpriced for a sandwich meal at an old walk-up fast food joint (with no indoor seating) in Alhambra.
FOOD:  The food was served hot and freshly prepared.  The sandwich was standard in size (on a standard roll), but overflowing in pastrami.  It was A LOT of pastrami. The pastrami itself was good and juicy, but nothing special.  The small/medium fries were actually extra large fries (I was given a paper lunch bag half full of fries).  The fries were thick and good, but also A LOT.  The drink (horchata) was too sugary.  I had to water down the horchata to drink it.
SUMMARY: This is an OKAY place for pastrami, but definitely not a place I would crave or make an effort to return to, especially not at those prices.<//Review>

<Pics>None</Pics><Review>I have been here several times. The prices seem quite high given that you're essentially ordering a sandwich. I paid about $25 for two sandwiches and fries. But when you open the sandwiches, you'll find a GENEROUS portion. I ordered two pastrami dip sandwiches. And they did NOT skimp on the pastrami! So much pastrami!

The sandwich was pretty salty, however. And the fries portion was enormous! I ordered a small and it looked like they gave me enough for a party of 6. I really tried to eat as much as I could but only could eat about half of them. You definitely get what you pay for here. But I would recommend drinking tons of fluids (water, preferably) as the sodium content here is probably through the roof.</Review><Rate>3</Rate><name>Curtis Chan<//name>< date>

<user>101766142773357400354<//user><name>Pea Gee< /name>< Time>
1538024036079< /Time>
<Rating>4<//Rating><review>The food here is decent tasting good but nothing extraordinary. What IS extraordinary are the portions. WOW! I've never eaten at The Hat so I walked up and ordered like I normally do at any burger joint. I ordered a pastrami dip for me, one for my husband, a cheeseburger for each of my two kids, an order of fries, an order of onion rings for my husband and chili cheese fries for me. They don't have meal "combos" so I figured I'd make up my own. BIG mistake lol. My hubby and I were hard pressed to finish HALF of one pastrami, much less a full one. We all picked from the chili cheese fries and still had at least half to bring home with us. We each had one or two onion rings just to taste them and sampled a fry or two as well. We ended up overstuffed and still had about 2/3 of our meal left over. Like I said, the food is typical L.A. fast food, tasty but nothing life changing but come hungry and bring someone to share with because ONE item off this menu is enough to fill you up plus have tasty leftover. FYI its is a bit pricey for fast food (all this plus four large drinks set us back $62) but keep in mind that you are paying for 3 or 4 times the normal burger joint servings. It's the perfect spot to come with a group, order a couple of items and share.<//review>< pics>
None< /pics>

< Review>
Still the go to place in SGV for hot pastrami after all these decades. Still no public toilets after all these decades. Same ok walk up sidewalk window. Seating area. Hasn't changed much in the 30 years since I went to high school. Try to stop by when I'm in So.Cal. Merging into traffic when leaving is still an adventure.</Review>

<date>1458176471894</date><Pics>None< /Pics>< Review>
The Hat, although a longstanding pastrami and burger spot, is not my cup of tea. While the location has history, the quality of the food does not warrant my business.

The pastrami is mediocre at best and not something that I would order again. Everything is pretty much mediocre to me, even the fries, which should at least be decent. But hey, everyone's tastes are different. I just have learned to go beyond reputation and care more about the quality of the food I am spending towards.</Review>

< name>
Irene Figueroa</name>
< time>
1417761177428</time>
<Rate>5</Rate>< text>
I have been in the SGV for almost 10 years now and up until this year, had never tried The Hat. Boy that was a mistake. I LOVE IT. The pastrami sandwiches are HUGE and brimming with yummy pickles and mustard (the only way a sandwich should be in my opinion). The most recent time that I went, I got a pastrami sandwich and chili cheese fries to share with a friend. I should have known better than to assume that this was enough food to satisfy two people. It was more like a platter for 3-4. They put the chili cheese fries on top of a 4-compartment cup holder and it has a GENEROUS scoop of chili and cheese on top of the fries. I think I took 3 bites after finishing my half of the sandwich and called it quits. I need to go back and try to tame that beast one more time but this time, I'll bring more back up! >:]< /text>

<userid>102918253898437847981</userid><user_name>Rodney S< /user_name><Date>1492025337002< /Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
<review>The Hat, I tip my hat to thee!

If you need fries in caveman proportions, then look no further.  For The Hat, is where it's at!

The OG location that started it all, The Hat in Alhambra is an old school food stand, complete with walk-up windows for ordering & pick up, along with a covered patio dining area.  For my inaugural visit, I pondered whether to order their famous pastrami dip or go with their wet fries.  I've read how their servings of fries are quite generous, and being how I try not to eat bread, I thought an order of loaded wet fries was that particular day's calling.

Wet fries w/ added pastrami, tomatoes, pickles & mustard-
Holy crap!  It looks like a food challenge!  I thought the chatter about portions were simply hyperbole, like a tall tale being altered with exaggerations until the details became comical.  But, alas, I wasn't prepared for what lied before me.  I watched my order prepared right before my very eyes.  From thick fries fresh from the fryer, to the slathering of savory brown gravy, the addition of tender, juicy pastrami, to the addition of a pound of dill pickle slices & tomatoes, to the cherry on top being a delicious dollop of mustard, I saw the assemblage of this calorie-busting behemoth from birth to readiness graduation.  The customers after me marveled at the huge portions of my loaded wet fries being prepared, which, like a proud parent, I boasted "Yeah, that's mine."

After laying claim to a table, I dug into my gargantuan meal.  Each bite, wondrous & delightful.  The fries had the perfect thickness to handle the weight of all that smothered them.  The gravy salty & creamy.  The pastrami wonderfully fatty.  The amount of pickles seemed almost ridiculous.  After 5 minutes of going at it, the loaded wet fries seemed like I hardly put a dent in them.  They mocked me, saying "Is that the best you got, bub?"  I did my best to devour the most I could, knowing I'd have to take this monstrosity home to await it's final fate later on for dinner.

Besides the usual condiments, all you can grab whole chili peppers are a must if you're a heat lover.  They're a perfect compliment to the copious amounts of food at The Hat.

Service was good.  Ordering at the window was quick, and I didn't wait long for my fries to be ready.  Ample tables to dine at, with parking in a private lot.  The Hat is conveniently located minutes north of the 10 freeway at the intersection of Valley & Garfield.

Hunger need not show it's ugly head here.  The Hat serves ginormous amounts of food quickly for the famished masses.  I managed to finish my loaded wet fries after 2 meals.  This coming from a guy with a healthy appetite.  I'd imagine some might go a whole day to accomplish that.  Of course, sharing would be a good idea, but I'm not into that.  I want this baby all to myself.  My first visit here, and I see why The Hat is a beloved SGV institution.  If I'm in the area again, and I don't care about calories & BMI, then I'm definitely dropping by for another go at The Hat.

Highly recommend!
NOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOM<//review>< pics>
None<//pics>

<text>So I heard from people and friends I must try this place out so I did and decided to come to this location. It reminded me so much of Tommys Burgers because its at the corner of both busy mainstreets. So the menu of this place didnt surprise me as much as I thought it would but for its price its cheap. So I decided to order the BBQ Beef Pastrami here and a side of onion rings. The moment you bit the Pastrami Beef BBQ sandwich all I tasted was the BBQ. It felt like there was no meat here :/ and the sauce its self has overwhelmed the beef by 90%. But other than that the onion rings did not dissapoint me they were worth buying it cost $4 something and were given alot in the bag. Other than that this place was a good experience next time Ill just order the regular pastrami sandwich instead.< /text>< Pictures>

< Text>
My little Brother Steve (RIP Steve)  and I got a pastrami every time we went to the Theatre across the st, I think The Garfield. They were on a French roll , piled high, then drenched in gravy, cost 65 CENTS. The pool at Granada Park was 20 cents; we earned $ 2 to cut lawns. Best sandwhich in my 71 years. That was 1951 / 52, moved from Alhambra in 1961, boo hoo. My friend ( Butch Rozelle ) , pushed me off the wall around the Castle ( where Phil Spector killed Lana Clarkson years later ) I was semi-conscious for awhile; awoke 3 days later to find the Rozelle's had left town....
hi butch you still around ?< /Text>
